to after she sat down with the immigration officer in tiny office we and bunch of people from other countries with similar hopes were placed in rooms with tiny beds in them hotel full of these rooms it was and my mom and two other families in little room waiting for somebody to come in and let us know if we were going to be granted permission to enter the us or be sent back some people spent days there some spent weeks in agonizing anxiety over what the answer would be meanwhile i was wondering when the heck we were going to get to disney we were there only day when we finally got the news the room bursted with joy everybody around clapping and hugging and screaming and crying and yelling out yay we re all going to disney little did i know little and my mama ended up on greyhound bus to miami that took hours — that s where i have my most vivid memories other stuff i vaguely remember and know from stories my parents told years after but i remember writing in my winnie the pooh journal lot on that bus ride we got to miami and moved into my grandpa s colleague s house who later became my godmother my mom was very good architect in cuba but when she came to america none of the degrees she earned in cuba counted so to make enough to keep us fed and put into school she began stacking shoes in marshalls and going to school at night to take courses in english all while taking to and from school and helping with my homework all by herself alone in strange country i can t imagine how frustrating it must have been for her to have worked her whole life in architecture and then have it all erased when she came here one day as if god was listening two elderly cuban women were conversing with her and told her oye bonita trabajar marshalls where are you from my mom told her the story of how she was cuban and she was actually an architect you wouldn t believe it but the two cuban women said they had brother who worked in architecture and needed someone who worked in autocad complicated architectural computer program they asked her do you know autocad internally my mom was like autocad what the hell is autocad we use pencil and paper where i m from but to the ladies she said autocad of course yes of course i can do that she learned how to use the program in week and made enough to move us out of my godmother s house and into an apartment she learned fast because she literally had to in order to survive immigrants have one thing in common hunger i don t mean it literally although that s true too but metaphorically the hunger to do the impossible because you have choice because you came too damn far because you ve known what struggling is and you re not going to take an opportunity for granted the hunger and ability to win above people with better circumstances than you simply because you want it badly enough long story short my papa came over from mexico year and half later — i had little calendar in my room counting down the days — because couldn t stand being away from us went through such hardship to cross the mexican border and had it harder than my mom and i did literally risking his life for his family to physically make it here when first came to the us started off washing cars in front of dolphin mall in the blistering miami heat but we kept moving on up with the latin community in miami helping each other up as we did it slowly and slowly my parents kept working and climbing and ended up forming construction company together named after my sister and i they always pushed to focus on my studies because the whole reason we came here was so my sister and i could have better opportunities in life than they did they said money comes and goes but your education aqui and they would point to my head while saying that nobody can ever take that away from you they let know that in order to go good college i had to get scholarship so i worked as hard as i could however — plot twist — that didn t quite go the way we thought it would you see in th grade little girl who had never sung in front of people before asked her parents if they could take her to greensboro nc to audition for little show called the x factor yikes i had never sang in front of people before well did my mom know autocad did i know how to perform on stage on tv but i wanted it badly enough and i learned from my family that if you work hard enough and you want it badly enough you can do the impossible i was wrong about one thing my mama and papa did not leave everything behind they brought it with them my grandma still makes pork and rice and beans every holiday like she did and my mom still feels the waves of the malecon in her heartbeat because she still feels the most at peace when she s by the my grandma and dad still get drunk and sing luis miguel in the kitchen we found our favorite taco spot in miami i capitalized taco because they are that good and whenever we find another person from our country we freak out ¿de parte because we have home in us because we brought it with us every cuban brought it with them and so we have miami mexicans brought it and so we have the best mexican food ever the italians brought it and so we have pizza the swedish brought it and we have great pop songs the list goes on and on and so that s why when i hear bigoted racist man with power and influence speak with anger and ill will about immigrants i think what fool i am so proud to be cuban mexican this country was built on immigrants people who were brave enough to start over how strong we are to leave behind everything we know in hopes of something better we are not fearless we just have dreams bigger than our fears we jump we run we swim we move mountains we do whatever it takes and so next time when anybody wants to tell you they want to build wall on our border remember behind that wall is struggle determination hunger behind that wall could be the next cure for cancer the next scientist the next artist the next drummer the next anything they work hard enough to become p s i did end up going to disney for the first time year later
